1 Climate change and temperature anomalies

If we wanted to study climate change, we can find data on the Combined Land-Surface Air and Sea-Surface Water Temperature Anomalies in the Northern Hemisphere at NASA’s Goddard Institute for Space Studies. The tabular data of temperature anomalies can be found here

To define temperature anomalies you need to have a reference, or base, period which NASA clearly states that it is the period between 1951-1980.

weather <- 
  read_csv("https://data.giss.nasa.gov/gistemp/tabledata_v3/NH.Ts+dSST.csv", 
           skip = 1, 
           na = "***")
tidyweather <- weather %>%
  select(Year:Dec) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols=c('Jan':'Dec'),names_to="Month",values_to="delta")

1.1 Plotting Information

Let us plot the data using a time-series scatter plot, and add a trendline. To do that, we first need to create a new variable called date in order to ensure that the delta values are plot chronologically.

In the following chunk of code, I used the argument, which does not run a chunk of code; I did so that you can knit the document before tidying the data and creating a new dataframe tidyweather. When you actually want to run this code and knit your document, you must delete , not just here but in all chunks were appears.

tidyweather <- tidyweather %>%
  mutate(date = ymd(paste(as.character(Year), Month, "1")),
         month = month(date, label=TRUE),
         year = year(date))

ggplot(tidyweather, aes(x=date, y = delta))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(color="red") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs (
    title = "Weather Anomalies"
  )

Is the effect of increasing temperature more pronounced in some months?

It is sometimes useful to group data into different time periods to study historical data. For example, we often refer to decades such as 1970s, 1980s, 1990s etc. to refer to a period of time. NASA calcuialtes a temperature anomaly, as difference form the base periof of 1951-1980. The code below creates a new data frame called comparison that groups data in five time periods: 1881-1920, 1921-1950, 1951-1980, 1981-2010 and 2011-present.

comparison <- tidyweather %>% 
  filter(Year>= 1881) %>%     #remove years prior to 1881
  #create new variable 'interval', and assign values based on criteria below:
  mutate(interval = case_when(
    Year %in% c(1881:1920) ~ "1881-1920",
    Year %in% c(1921:1950) ~ "1921-1950",
    Year %in% c(1951:1980) ~ "1951-1980",
    Year %in% c(1981:2010) ~ "1981-2010",
    TRUE ~ "2011-present"
  ))
ggplot(comparison, aes(x=delta, fill=interval))+
  geom_density(alpha=0.2) +   #density plot with tranparency set to 20%
  theme_bw() +                #theme
  labs (
    title = "Density Plot for Monthly Temperature Anomalies",
    y     = "Density"         #changing y-axis label to sentence case
  )

#creating yearly averages
average_annual_anomaly <- tidyweather %>% 
  group_by(Year) %>%   #grouping data by Year
  
  # creating summaries for mean delta 
  # use `na.rm=TRUE` to eliminate NA (not available) values 
  summarise(annual_average_delta = mean(delta, na.rm=TRUE)) 

#plotting the data:
ggplot(average_annual_anomaly, aes(x=Year, y= annual_average_delta))+
  geom_point() +
  
  #Fit the best fit line, using LOESS method
  geom_smooth() +
  
  #change to theme_bw() to have white background + black frame around plot
  theme_bw() +
  labs (
    title = "Average Yearly Anomaly",
    y     = "Average Annual Delta"
  )

1.2 Confidence Interval for delta

NASA points out on their website that

A one-degree global change is significant because it takes a vast amount of heat to warm all the oceans, atmosphere, and land by that much. In the past, a one- to two-degree drop was all it took to plunge the Earth into the Little Ice Age.

formula_ci <- comparison %>% 
  filter(interval=="2011-present",!is.na(delta)) %>% 
  summarize(
    Average=mean(delta),
    Std_Dev=sd(delta),
    count=n(),
    Std_Err=Std_Dev/(sqrt(count)),
    Critical_Value=qt(0.95,count-1),
    Margin_Error=Std_Err*Critical_Value,
    Conf_Interval_Lower=Average-Margin_Error,
    Conf_Interval_Upper=Average+Margin_Error)
  # calculate lower/upper 95% CI
  

  # calculate summary statistics for temperature deviation (delta)

set.seed(1234)
boot.temperature<-comparison %>% 
  filter(interval=="2011-present",!is.na(delta)) %>% 
  specify(response=delta) %>% 
  generate(reps=1000,type="bootstrap") %>%
  calculate(stat="mean")

CI<-boot.temperature %>% 
  get_confidence_interval(level=0.95,type="percentile")

# use the infer package to construct a 95% CI for delta

What is the data showing us? Please type your answer after (and outside!) this blockquote. You have to explain what you have done, and the interpretation of the result. One paragraph max, please!

First, we set the seed so R samples the same sample each time, so that our results will be the same when we (or someone else) reproduces them. Then, we filtered the data for the timeframe we wanted (2011-present), and cleared out any rows with empty delta values. We generated 1000 resamples of delta values with 103 observations in each, all in this specified time period with the sampling method boostrapping: sampling with replacement, meaning that if our sample space were a hat, whatever you take out of the hat, you have to put back into it before taking another sample out. Then we calculated the mean for 1000 samples, and from these sample means, we calculated the 95% confidence interval (displayed above) which means that there is a 95% chance that this confidence interval contains the true population mean.

2.1 Instagram and Snapchat, by sex

Can we estimate the population proportion of Snapchat or Instagram users in 2016?

  1. Create a new variable, snap_insta that is Yes if the respondent reported using any of Snapchat (snapchat) or Instagram (instagrm), and No if not. If the recorded value was NA for both of these questions, the value in your new variable should also be NA.
library(dplyr)

gss_new<- gss %>%  
  mutate(snap_insta = case_when(
    snapchat=="NA" & instagrm=="NA" ~ "NA",
    snapchat=="Yes"| instagrm=="Yes" ~ "Yes",
    TRUE ~ "No"))
  1. Calculate the proportion of Yes’s for snap_insta among those who answered the question, i.e. excluding NAs.
gss_new_proportion<- gss_new %>%
  filter(!is.na(snap_insta)) %>%
  group_by(sex) %>% 
  mutate(user = case_when(
    snap_insta=="Yes" ~ 1,
    TRUE ~ 0)) %>% 
  summarise(Total=length(user), Yes_answers=sum(user)) %>%
  mutate(Proportion=Yes_answers/Total)

gss_new_proportion

  1. Using the CI formula for proportions, please construct 95% CIs for men and women who used either Snapchat or Instagram
gss_new_proportion %>%

3.2 Compare Confidence Intervals

Compare the confidence intervals for week 15 (6-12 April 2020) and week 34 (17-23 August 2020). Can you explain what’s going on? One paragraph would be enough.

The confidence interval in week 34 is wider than in week 15, which means that Trump’s approval rating had a bigger dispersion from 17-23 August, than from 6-12 April.   1. What is the relationship between HIV prevalence and life expectancy? Generate a scatterplot with a smoothing line to report your results. You may find faceting useful

Base on the graph below, we can see that the HIV prevalence and life expectancy are inversely related. The lower the prevalence of HIV in a country, the higher the life expectancy while on the flip side, the higher the prevalence of HIV, the lower the life expectancy. This relationship makes sense as HIV is one of the highest causes of mortality in the world and hence a person’s life expectancy would radically decrease should they contract HIV.

2. What is the relationship between fertility rate and GDP per capita? Generate a scatterplot with a smoothing line to report your results. You may find facetting by region useful

The overall relationship between fertility rate and GDP per capita is that the lower the GDP per capita, the higher the fertility rate. This could be explained due to the fact that the those with a lower income may not be able to afford contraceptives and hence they have a higher birth rate per woman. This trend continues to around $50,000, when the trend reverses and there is a slight increase in the fertility rate as GDP per capita increases. This could be due to the fact that the higher your income, the more likely you would be able to afford healthcare and hence be able to increase ones fertility.

  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth()

4. How has mortality rate for under 5 changed by region? In each region, find the top 5 countries that have seen the greatest improvement, as well as those 5 countries where mortality rates have had the least improvement or even deterioration.

  1. Is there a relationship between primary school enrollment and fertility rate?

There is a relationship between primary school enrollment and fertility rate. The higher the primary school enrollment, the lower the fertility rate. This could be explained by a variety of factors. For one, an increase in enrollment would mean less children are out of school and hence lower the chances of child marriages which in turn would decrease the fertility rate. Furthermore, an increase in enrollment would also mean an increase in education and hence greater prevalence of contraceptives could be used to lower the fertility rate.

At the same time, the fertility rate could also affect the primary school enrollment. With a higher fertility rate, which is most commonly found in less economically well of communities, this could also mean a diminishing ability to afford primary school education with every increase in children. This would mean as families have more kids, they would be less likely to afford to send their children to school and hence a decrease in primary school enrollment in these communities.

  ggplot(aes(x=school_enrollment, y= fertility_rate))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth()

Given the data we have, I would like you to produce two graphs that show death % rate:

  1. by age group, sex, and whether the patient had co-morbidities or not
  2. by age group, sex, and whether the patient was admited to Intensive Care Unit (ICU) or not.
# Filter and summarize count, for grouped data, with death criteria
grouped_med_death <- covid_data %>%
  filter(medcond_yn %in% c("Yes", "No"),        # Get rid of "Unknown" or "Missing" medcond_yn
         death_yn %in% c("Yes", "No"),          # Get rid of "Missing" death_yn
         death_yn != "Unknown",                 # Get rid of "Unknown" death_yn
         sex %in% c("Male", "Female"),          # Get rid of sex other than "Male" and "Female"
         age_group != "Unknown") %>%            # Get rid of age_group "Unknown"
  group_by(age_group, sex, medcond_yn, death_yn) %>%           # Group, with "Yes" or "No" as separate categories for death_yn
  summarise(N=n())                              # Obtain count for combinations of categories

# Filter and summarize count, for grouped data, without death criteria
grouped_med <- covid_data %>%
  filter(medcond_yn %in% c("Yes", "No"),
         death_yn %in% c("Yes", "No"),
         death_yn != "Unknown",
         sex %in% c("Male", "Female"),
         age_group != "Unknown") %>%
  group_by(age_group, sex, medcond_yn) %>%                     # Group, regardless of "Yes" or "No" for death_yn
  summarise(TN=n())

# Join categorical count and total count, calculate death rate
plot_comorbidities <- grouped_med_death %>%
  left_join(grouped_med, by = c("age_group", "sex", "medcond_yn")) %>%         # Present total count next to sub-count
  mutate(death_rate = N / TN * 100,                                                    # Create new column of calculated percentage of total
         medcond_yn = factor(medcond_yn,                                               # Factorize and rename medcond_yn feature
                             levels = c("Yes", "No"),
                             labels = c("With comorbidities",
                                        "Without comorbidities"))) %>%
  filter(death_yn == "Yes")      # Only use death_rate (not non-death rate) before plotting

# Plot
ggplot(plot_comorbidities, aes(x = age_group, y = death_rate)) +               # Specify data and axes
  geom_col(fill = "#365383") +                                                    # Specify chart style (bar) and fill color
  geom_text(mapping = aes(y = death_rate + 3, label = round(death_rate,1)), size = 4) +  # Specify data labels and their positions
  coord_flip() +                                                               # Flip axis
  facet_grid(medcond_yn ~ sex) +                                               # Create a grid format (vertical ~ horizontal)
  labs(x="", 
       y = "", 
       title = "Covid death % by age group, sex and presence of co-morbidities") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 60, 20),
                     labels = paste(seq(0, 60, 20), "%")) +
  theme_bw()

#Getting monthly expected values 
monthly_exp <- bike %>%
  filter(year %in% c("2015", "2016", "2017", "2018", "2019")) %>% #filtered by years to exclude 2020
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarize(monthly_mean = mean(bikes_hired))

#Getting monthly actual rents
monthly_rent <- bike %>%
  filter(year > 2014) %>%
  group_by(year, month) %>%
  summarize(real_rents = mean(bikes_hired))

#Merging the two data frames above to have one data frame wih all information and creating the variable excess rentals
monthly_rent_and_ex <- merge(x = monthly_rent, y = monthly_exp, by = "month", all.x=TRUE) %>%
  mutate(excess_rentals = real_rents - monthly_mean)
  

#plotting graphs 
monthly_dist  <- ggplot(monthly_rent_and_ex, aes(y = monthly_mean, x = month, group =year)) +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = ifelse(excess_rentals > 0, monthly_mean, real_rents), ymax = monthly_mean), fill = "red", alpha = 0.2) +
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = ifelse(excess_rentals < 0, monthly_mean, real_rents), ymax = monthly_mean), fill = "green", alpha = 0.2) +
  geom_line(aes(y = real_rents), alpha = 0.2) +
  geom_line(color = "blue", aes(y = monthly_mean, group = 1)) +
  labs(title = "Monthly changes in TfL bike rentals", subtitle = "Change from monthly average shown in blue and calculated between 2015-2019", y = "Bike rentals", x ="") +
  facet_wrap(~ year) +
  theme_minimal()

#Getting weekly expected values 
weekly_average_df <- bike %>%

weekly_real_df <- bike %>%

  mutate(percentage_diff = (excess_rentals/weekly_average)*100)

#Plotting the percentage difference per real rents per week and expected rents per week 
weekly_plot <- ggplot(weekly_average_and_real_df, aes(x = week, y = percentage_diff)) +

For both of these graphs, you have to calculate the expected number of rentals per week or month between 2015-2019 and then, see how each week/month of 2020 compares to the expected rentals. Think of the calculation excess_rentals = actual_rentals - expected_rentals.

Should you use the mean or the median to calculate your expected rentals? Why? If we use the median, we can avoid outliers than can move our mean significantly towards one way, but in this case we chose the mean since the plot explicitly says “average”.
